SIMPLE: figure
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Figure
<hw>Fig"ure</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧g"⟦usl⟧r; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.,
<ets>figure</ets>, L. <ets>figura</ets>; akin to <ets>fingere</ets> to
form, shape, feign. See <er>Feign</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The form
of anything; shape; outline; appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flowers have all exquisite <qex>figures</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The representation of any form, as by drawing,
painting, modeling, carving, embroidering, etc.; especially, a
representation of the human body; <as>as, a <ex>figure</ex> in bronze; a
<ex>figure</ex> cut in marble.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A coin that bears the <qex>figure</qex> of an angel.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pattern in cloth, paper, or other manufactured
article; a design wrought out in a fabric; <as>as, the muslin was of a
pretty <ex>figure</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A diagram or drawing, made to
represent a magnitude or the relation of two or more magnitudes; a
surface or space inclosed on all sides; -- called <xex>superficial</xex>
when inclosed by lines, and <xex>solid</xex> when inclosed by surfaces;
any arrangement made up of points, lines, angles, surfaces,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The appearance or impression made by the conduct or
career of a person; <as>as, a sorry <ex>figure</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I made some <qex>figure</qex> there.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gentlemen of the best <qex>figure</qex> in the county.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Distinguished appearance; magnificence; conspicuous
representation; splendor; show.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That he may live in <qex>figure</qex> and indulgence.</q>
<rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A character or symbol representing a number; a
numeral; a digit; as, 1, 2,3, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Value, as expressed in numbers; price; <as>as, the
goods are estimated or sold at a low <ex>figure</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With nineteen thousand a year at the very lowest
<qex>figure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A person, thing, or action, conceived of as
analogous to another person, thing, or action, of which it thus becomes
a type or representative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who is the <qex>figure</qex> of Him that was to come.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. v. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A mode of expressing abstract or
immaterial ideas by words which suggest pictures or images from the
physical world; pictorial language; a trope; hence, any deviation from
the plainest form of statement. Also called a <altname>figure of
speech</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To represent the imagination under the <qex>figure</qex> of a
wing.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>The form of a syllogism with
respect to the relative position of the middle term.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Dancing)</fld> <def>Any one of the several regular
steps or movements made by a dancer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>A horoscope; the diagram of
the aspects of the astrological houses.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Music)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any short
succession of notes, either as melody or as a group of chords, which
produce a single complete and distinct impression.</def>
<rj><au>Grove.</au></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A form of melody or accompaniment kept up through a
strain or passage; a musical phrase or motive; a florid
embellishment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ Figures are often written upon the staff in music to
denote the kind of measure. They are usually in the form of a fraction,
the upper figure showing how many notes of the kind indicated by the
lower are contained in one measure or bar. Thus, <musfig>2/4</musfig>
signifies that the measure contains two quarter notes. The following are
the principal figures used for this purpose: -- <-- the "figures"
illustrated here have a bar through each number and cannot be
represented as simple fractions, thus the special "musfig" field
notation. The following numbers are contained in a single line of large
(ca. 14 pt.) bold type --></p>

<p><musfig>2/2</musfig><musfig>2/4</musfig><musfig>2/8</musfig>
<musfig>4/2</musfig><musfig>2/4</musfig><musfig>4/8</musfig>
<musfig>3/2</musfig><musfig>3/4</musfig><musfig>3/8</musfig>
<musfig>6/4</musfig><musfig>6/4</musfig><musfig>6/8</musfig>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Academy figure</b></col>, <col><b>Canceled
figures</b></col>, <col><b>Lay figure</b></col>, etc.</mcol> <cd>See
under <er>Academy</er>, <er>Cancel</er>, <er>Lay</er>, etc.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Figure caster</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Figure
flinger</b></col></mcol>, <cd>an astrologer.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧This
<xex>figure caster</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> -- <col><b>Figure
flinging</b></col>, <cd>the practice of astrology.</cd> --
<col><b>Figure-of-eight knot</b></col>, <cd>a knot shaped like the
figure 8. See <xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Knot</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Figure painting</b></col>, <cd>a picture of the human figure, or
the act or art of depicting the human figure.</cd> -- <col><b>Figure
stone</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>agalmatolite.</cd> --
<col><b>Figure weaving</b></col>, <cd>the art or process of weaving
figured fabrics.</cd> -- <col><b>To cut a figure</b></col>, <cd>to make
a display.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>Sir W. Scott.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Figure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Figure
<hw>Fig"ure</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Figured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Figuring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>figurer</ets>, L.
<ets>figurare</ets>, fr. <ets>figura</ets>. See <er>Figure</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To represent by a figure, as to
form or mold; to make an image of, either palpable or ideal; also, to
fashion into a determinate form; to shape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If love, alas! be pain I bear,</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No thought can <qex>figure</qex>, and no tongue
declare.Prior.</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To embellish with design; to adorn with
figures.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The vaulty top of heaven⟦br⟧
<qex>Figured</qex> quite o'er with burning meteors.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To indicate by numerals; also, to compute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As through a crystal glass the <qex>figured</qex> hours are
seen.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To represent by a metaphor; to signify or
symbolize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose white vestments <qex>figure</qex> innocence.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To prefigure; to foreshow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In this the heaven <qex>figures</qex> some event.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To write over or
under the bass, as figures or other characters, in order to indicate the
accompanying chords.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To embellish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To figure out</b></col>, <cd>to solve; to compute or find
the result of.</cd> -- <col><b>To figure up</b></col>, <cd>to add; to
reckon; to compute the amount of.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Figure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Figure
<hw>Fig"ure</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a figure; to
be distinguished or conspicious; <as>as, the envoy <ex>figured</ex> at
court</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sociable, hospitable, eloquent, admired, <qex>figuring</qex> away
brilliantly.</q> <rj><qau>M. Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To calculate; to contrive; to scheme; <as>as, he is
<ex>figuring</ex> to secure the nomination</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>go figure</b></col> <cd>a phrase used by itself as an
interjection to mean ⟦ldquo⟧How can one explain that?⟦rdquo⟧, or to
express puzzlement over some seeming contradiction.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Figured</ent>⟦br⟧
